how do i say have you lost your mind in german i'd like to say have you lost your friggin' mind or are you out of your mind you've made a fool out of yourself at the party have you lost your mind literally translates as hast du den verstand verloren but as you want to express the friggin' also you might rather say sag mal spinnst du total that is a lot more colloquial than the first one and most likely to be heard in this situation the whole sentence is sag mal spinnst du du hast dich auf der party vollkommen zum deppen idioten gemacht other expressions like this are with litteral translations nicht mehr alle tassen im schrank haben to not have all cups in your cupboard anymore eine schraube locker haben to have a loose screw einen vogel haben to have a bird German grammar Germish Ludwig Quidde Die __rzte The Longest Day (film) Nazi songs A Mighty Fortress is Our God Grimm's Fairy Tales Rammstein Hannes Wader Volker Schl__ndorff Hiberno-English Lukas Resetarits Ernst J__nger Subjunctive mood G__tz George Eppstein Reinhard Mey Vicky Leandros Schubert compositions D number 505-998 Krupp Trial Gott erhalte Franz den Kaiser German school of swordsmanship Motet Korean language The Creation Deutsch Amerikanische Freundschaft Die Wacht am Rhein Herzeleid (album) Ludwig Schl__fli Die Toten Hosen Symphony No. 10 (Mahler) Kurt Raab Die Zauberfl__te Das Lied der Deutschen Berlin Wilhelm Wundt Shrine of the Three Kings at Cologne Cathedral Auferstanden aus Ruinen Gustav Freytag Sebastian Haffner Gender-neutral language Helga Zepp-LaRouche Anschluss Udo J__rgens Friedrich Nietzsche Relative clause Heinrich B__ll __lafur El__asson Preterite Mack the Knife Peter Sloterdijk Alfred D__blin Hans Fallada National Socialist German Workers Party Berlin Lehrter Bahnhof Dative case Ernst Th__lmann Pioneer Organisation Lithuanian language Reality Swiss Labour Party Gothic language Ein deutsches Requiem Cognate Dodo Martin Chemnitz Vienna Kurt Tucholsky Andreas Hillgruber Erich von Manstein